            "title": "Oil gains 3% as fragile ceasefire, Hormuz keep supply risks elevated",
            "description": "<div class=\"txt-s4 article-text\"><p>STORY: Oil prices rose on Thursday (April 9).</p><p>\n              Markets were concerned about whether a two-week Middle East ceasefire will hold up.</p><!-- Article --><p>\n              And were unsure about energy flows through the Strait of Hormuz.</p><p>\n              Brent crude futures were up around 3%, at roughly $98 a barrel.</p><p>\n              While U.S. West Texas Intermediate crude also rose by a similar amount to just under $98.</p><p>\n              Both benchmarks fell below $100 per barrel in the previous trading session.</p><p>\n              That was on optimism the U.S.-Iranian ceasefire would result in the strait reopening.</p><p>\n              But analysts still saw geopolitical risk, and there was no clarity on what U.S.-Iran talks would mean for oil flows.</p><p>\n              The Strait of Hormuz connects supply from Gulf producers to global markets.</p><p>\n              And it usually carries about a fifth of global oil and gas supply.</p><p>\n              Shippers on Wednesday said they needed clarity on terms of the ceasefire before they continued transiting through the Strait of Hormuz.</p><p>\n              Iranian media reported the country has issued maps to guide ships around mines and showing safe paths for passage.</p><p>\n              Regional oil facilities also stayed under threat.</p><p>\n              An oil industry source said Iran struck sites in nearby countries after the ceasefire.</p><p>\n              It included a pipeline in Saudi Arabia which has been used to bypass the Strait of Hormuz.</p></div>",
            "link": "https://hk.marketscreener.com/news/oil-gains-3-as-fragile-ceasefire-hormuz-keep-supply-risks-elevated-ce7e50dbd08df42d",
            "pub_date": "2026-04-09 20:36:11",
            "source": "marketscreener",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
